            <fr:title text="The weakest reflexive logic">The weakest reflexive logic</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>As an example that we'll make some use of in a moment, note that there is a reflexive logic that's weaker than every reflexive logic; let's call this one the <html:strong>weakest reflexive logic</html:strong>, or WRL:</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>8</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/006F/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>006F</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/006F/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Weakest reflexive logic, WRL">Weakest reflexive logic, WRL</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>The <html:strong>weakest reflexive logic</html:strong>, also called <html:strong>WRL</html:strong>, is the logic that contains any argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  = \{A\}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>The definition just tells you what WRL is; it doesn't actually show that WRL really is weaker than every reflexive logic.
But you now know enough to see that it is.
For a logic to be reflexive means that it contains every argument of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \;/\; A]]></fr:tex>---but these arguments are exactly the ones valid in WRL.
So every argument valid in WRL is valid in any reflexive logic; that shows that WRL is weaker than every reflexive logic.</html:p>
            <html:p>Note also that WRL is itself reflexive: it itself contains every argument of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \;/\; A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
